Victor Osimhen has described the Serie A best U-23 player award as a great milestone in his blossoming career. Osimhen who helped Napoli to finish in the top three in Serie A to secure a Champions League spot. He said: “For me, this is a great milestone! After spending a lot of time difficult, due to multiple injuries and all, I still held out against all odds but I won’t be able to do these things without the support of my family, friends, fans, And of course my teammates and coaches, I appreciate you sincerely. “This is also for the people who want to see me fail, you motivate me all to shame many of you. Hello and see you next season, God is the greatest, let’s move,” he added. Meanwhile, was an unhappy return to the Emirates Stadium in London for Alex Iwobi as Everton were thrashed 5-1 by Arsenal on the final day of the English Premier League.   Heavy downpour stops Zenith Bank swimming gala     GOtv Boxing Night 25: Emirates fires Adama warning     Prudent Energy H’ball Premier League: Kano Pillars, Safety…   Meanwhile, Leicester City finished the season with a 4-1 rout of Southampton at the King Power Stadium. After a goalless first half, goals from James Maddison, Jamie Vardy, and Ayoze Pérez (2) earned Brendan Rodgers’ side a comprehensive win. James Ward-Prowse pulled one back for the visitors. Ademola Lookman played the last 13 minutes for the Foxes while teammate Kelechi Iheanacho was on the bench. Eagles Vice-captain William Troost-Ekong watched from the bench as Watford lost 2-1 to Chelsea at Stamford Bridge while his international teammates Oghenekaro Etebo, Emmanuel Dennis, and Samuel Kalu were not named in the matchday squad. Frank Onyeka was a non-playing substitute as Brentford and Leeds United shared the spoils with a 1-1 draw at the Brentford Community Stadium. It was the midfielder’s first squad involvement for a Premier League game since going off injured with an ankle injury in the World Cup playoff against Ghana.